Creating a Simple Webpage: Design a basic webpage that includes text, images, and links. Use common HTML tags like h1, p, a, img, and ul or ol. Structure a webpage with semantic tags such as header, footer, nav, section, and article. Ensure the content is well-organized for readability and SEO.

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <meta name="description" content="A simple webpage showcasing HTML elements">
    <title>My Simple Webpage</title>
</head>
<body>

    <!-- Header Section -->
    <header>
        <h1>Welcome to My Simple Webpage</h1>
        <nav>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#home">Home</a></li>
                <li><a href="#about">About</a></li>
                <li><a href="#contact">Contact</a></li>
            </ul>
        </nav>
    </header>

    <!-- Main Content Section -->
    <main>
        <section id="home">
            <h2>Home</h2>
            <p>This is the home section of my webpage. Here you will find an introduction to the content.</p>
            <img src="image.jpg" alt="A beautiful scenery" width="600">
        </section>

        <section id="about">
            <h2>About Me</h2>
            <article>
                <p>Hi! I am a web enthusiast learning HTML and web design. This is an example of how to structure a simple webpage.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Learning HTML</li>
                    <li>Building websites</li>
                    <li>Exploring web design</li>
                </ul>
            </article>
        </section>

        <section id="contact">
            <h2>Contact</h2>
            <p>If you'd like to get in touch, feel free to <a href="mailto:someone@example.com">email me</a>.</p>
        </section>
    </main>

    <!-- Footer Section -->
    <footer>
        <p>&copy; 2024 My Simple Webpage. All rights reserved.</p>
    </footer>

</body>
</html>
